TY  - JOUR
T1  - Jennifer Lee and Min Zhou's The Asian American Achievement Paradox
AN  - 1817595733
AB  - Why is an increasingly diverse American society simultaneously becoming more economically stratified? The dynamic and ever-shifting causes and consequences of rising income inequality demand that we move beyond facile and essentialist notions about who achieves and why. Race and ethnicity play critical roles in shaping opportunity structures and the distribution of resources, and immigration has long been understood in policy debates, scholarly inquiry, and American national narrative to be an important driver of the economic and social mobility of various racial and ethnic groups. Social science research is uniquely poised to explore these issues with textured nuance and analytical sophistication, offering much-needed interventions in a national conversation that can veer in directions that are hackneyed, inaccurate, and even irresponsible. We are therefore pleased to present this symposium on The Asian American Achievement Paradox, an important scholarly work with ‘real world’ utility that offers a fresh perspective on the dynamics of inequality by focusing on a group that has achieved a great deal of success over the last several decades: Asian Americans. Authored by sociologists Jennifer Lee and Min Zhou, the book leverages the fields of sociology, psychology, and Asian American Studies to weave together a detailed analysis at the structural, institutional, interpersonal, and individual levels. We have invited Patricia Fernández-Kelly, Amy Hsin, Tomás R. Jiménez, Philip Kasinitz, and Van C. Tran, five of today’s most prominent scholars of immigration, to offer commentary on how the book illuminates, challenges, and pushes the scholarship in important and useful new directions. They also offer thoughtful critiques as they engage with the core arguments of the book, and Lee and Zhou provide a Rejoinder to explore the questions raised and respond to the critiques.
